{"title_page": "HanWay Films", "text_new": "[[File:HanWay Films .jpg|thumb|Logo of HanWay Films]]\n'''HanWay Films''' is an independent British international sales, distribution and marketing company specializing in theatrical [[feature film]]s.\n\n==History==\nIn 1999, [[Jeremy Thomas]] founded international sales company HanWay Films with his colleagues Peter Watson (Deputy Chairman) and Stephan Mallmann, and continues to Chair the board. Two new members joined the board in 2011, Thorsten Schumacher, previously Head of Sales, was appointed Managing Director, and former Head of Business Affairs Jan Spielhoff took up the reins as Chief Operating Officer.\n\nHanWay has established itself as leading international sales, distribution and marketing company specialising in high-profile quality films from worldwide talent. HanWay arranges financing, sales and distribution for all films from Recorded Picture Company, along with projects from third party producers.\n\nHanWay also represents an extensive film catalogue of over 500 features including films from Thomas\u2019s [[Recorded Picture Company]], and the [[British Film Institute]]. Representing the very best in film-making talent, these include productions by [[Woody Allen]], [[Takeshi Kitano]], [[Bernardo Bertolucci]], [[Wim Wenders]], [[Terry Gilliam]], [[David Cronenberg]], [[Peter Greenaway]], [[Jean-Luc Godard]], [[David Mamet]], [[Milo\u0161 Forman]], [[Stephen Frears]], [[Phillip Noyce]] and [[Nagisa Oshima]].\n\n==Productions==\nHanWay\u2019s productions include Thomas' production of [[David Cronenberg]]'s ''[[A Dangerous Method]]'' starring [[Keira Knightley]], [[Viggo Mortensen]], [[Michael Fassbender]] and [[Vincent Cassel]], in the true-life story of the young [[Carl Jung|Dr. Jung]], his mentor [[Sigmund Freud|Freud]] and the beautiful patient that came between them; [[Lone Scherfig]]\u2019s coming-of-age drama ''[[An Education]]'', which won [[Carey Mulligan]] a [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]] award for [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Actress]];<ref>{{cite news |title=BAFTA Wins for Carey Mulligan and Colin Firth |date=2009-02-21 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8526670.stm\n|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=2010-04-02}}</ref> [[James Gunn]]\u2019s pop-culture actioner ''[[Super (2010 American film)|Super]]'' starring [[Rainn Wilson]], [[Ellen Page]] and [[Liv Tyler]], from producer [[Ted Hope]]; [[Nigel Cole]]\u2019s ''[[Made in Dagenham]]'' starring [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe]] nominee [[Sally Hawkins]] from producer [[Stephen Woolley]], and [[Andrea Arnold]]\u2019s adaptation of the romantic classic ''[[Wuthering Heights (2011 film)|Wuthering Heights]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=HanWay makes presales on 'Wuthering Heights' |first=Mimi |last=Turner |date=2010-03-01 |url=http://www.hollywoodreportereurope.com/hr/content_display/world/news/e3i23d773457742077cbd5a2ebc292fd5dd |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=2010-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOther films handled include ''[[Nowhere Boy]]'', a film by artist [[Sam Taylor-Johnson|Sam Taylor-Wood]] based on [[John Lennon]]\u2019s teenage years starring [[Aaron Taylor-Johnson|Aaron Johnson]]; [[Gurinder Chadha]]\u2019s culinary black comedy ''[[It's a Wonderful Afterlife]]'' which premiered at the 2010 [[Sundance Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite web |title=It's A Wonderful Afterlife to have Sundance Premiere |date=2010-11-01 |url=http://www.theasiannews.co.uk/entertainment/arts/s/1188647_its_a_wonderful_afterlife_to_have_sundance_premiere |work=The Asian News |accessdate=2010-04-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120915065003/http://www.theasiannews.co.uk/entertainment/arts/s/1188647_its_a_wonderful_afterlife_to_have_sundance_premiere |archivedate=2012-09-15 }}</ref>''[[Harry Brown (film)|Harry Brown]]'' starring [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] winner [[Michael Caine]]; [[Scott Hicks]]\u2019 Australian-set drama ''[[The Boys Are Back (film)|The Boys Are Back]]'' starring [[Clive Owen]]; Irish comedy ''[[Perrier's Bounty]],'' starring [[Cillian Murphy]] and [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] winner [[Jim Broadbent]]; and [[Danis Tanovi\u0107]]\u2019s ''[[Triage (film)|Triage]]'', with [[Colin Farrell]] in the lead. Theatrical documentary releases include [[Julien Temple]]\u2019s ''Oil City Confidential,'' and ''[[Mugabe and the White African]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=List of upcoming HanWay titles |first=Adam |last=Dawtrey |date=2008-10-31 |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117995092.html?categoryid=3310&cs=1&ref=ma|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=2010-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOther releases include [[Jon Amiel]]'s ''[[Creation (2009 film)|Creation]]'' starring [[Paul Bettany]] and [[Jennifer Connelly]] (produced by Thomas), which opened the 2009 [[Toronto International Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Toronto Film Festival Raises Curtain on Creation |first=Bob |last=Tourtellotte |date=2009-09-11 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE58A10K20090911|work=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=2010-04-02}}</ref>''[[Sunshine Cleaning]]'' starring [[Amy Adams]] and [[Emily Blunt]]; [[Gerald McMorrow]]\u2019s ''[[Franklyn]]'' starring [[Eva Green]], [[Ryan Phillippe]] and [[Sam Riley]] (produced by Thomas), [[Christopher Smith (director)|Christopher Smith]]\u2019s period thriller ''[[Black Death (film)|Black Death]]'' starring [[Sean Bean]], and [[Michael Winterbottom]]\u2019s ''[[Genova (2008 film)|Genova]]'' starring [[Colin Firth]].\n\nThe company also handled [[Takashi Miike]]\u2019s [[samurai]] epic ''[[13 Assassins (2010 film)|Thirteen Assassins]]'', and [[Jerzy Skolimowski]]'s political thriller ''[[Essential Killing]]'', both executive-produced by Thomas. Both films premiered at the [[67th Venice International Film Festival]], and ''Essential Killing'' went on to win the [[Special Jury Prize (Venice Film Festival)|Special Jury Prize]], [[Volpi Cup for Best Actor|Best Actor]] for [[Vincent Gallo]] (the [[Venice Film Festival|Volpi Cup]]), and the Cinemavenniere Award for Best Film in Competition (voted by a youth jury). Upcoming productions include films by [[David Cronenberg]], [[Terry Gilliam]] and [[Phillip Noyce]].\n\nThe company has previously handled such titles as [[Woody Allen]]\u2019s ''[[Match Point]]'', starring [[Scarlett Johansson]], [[Julian Jarrold]]\u2019s ''[[Becoming Jane]]'' starring [[Anne Hathaway]] and [[James McAvoy]], and [[Sarah Polley]]\u2019s multi-Academy Award nominated ''[[Away from Her]]'' starring [[Julie Christie]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Selected HanWay films of the past decade |first=Adam |last=Dawtrey |date=2008-10-31 |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117995098.html?categoryid=3310&ref=ra&cs=1|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=2010-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=HanWay takes on Polley, Jarrold projects to sell |first=Wendy |last=Mitchell |date=2005-11-04 |url=http://www.screendaily.com/hanway-takes-on-polley-jarrold-projects-to-sell/4025028.article|work=[[Screen International]]|accessdate=2010-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn its capacity as international sales agent, HanWay works closely with [[Ecosse Films]].\n\nHanWay Films represents collections from the [[British Film Institute]],<ref>{{cite web |title=HanWay takes on Library Sales for British Film Institute |first=Wendy |last=Mitchell |date=2008-03-17 |url=http://www.screendaily.com/hanway-takes-on-library-sales-for-british-film-institute/4037839.article | work=[[Screen International]] |accessdate=2010-04-02}}</ref> [[Merchant Ivory Productions|Merchant Ivory]],<ref>{{cite web |title=HanWay takes on Merchant Ivory Library |first=Wendy |last=Mitchell |date=2006-11-03 |url=http://www.screendaily.com/hanway-takes-on-merchant-ivory-library/4029451.article | work=[[Screen International]] |accessdate=2010-04-02}}</ref> [[Peter Weir]], [[Wim Wenders]], [[Phillip Noyce]], [[Jean Doumanian]], [[Alex Cox]], [[Paul Cox (director)|Paul Cox]], [[New Zealand Film Commission]], [[Manoel de Oliveira]] and [[Recorded Picture Company]], comprising some 500 [[feature film]]s, [[Documentary film|documentaries]] and [[animation]]s. This collection includes films from noted [[world cinema]] figures, including [[Woody Allen]], [[Bernardo Bertolucci]], [[David Cronenberg]], [[Clint Eastwood]], [[Milo\u0161 Forman]], [[Stephen Frears]], [[Terry Gilliam]], [[Alfred Hitchcock]], [[James Ivory]], [[Takeshi Kitano]], [[Bob Rafelson]], [[Terence Davies]], [[David Mamet]], [[Martin Scorsese]], and [[Ridley Scott]].\n\nWith ''[[Carol (film)|Carol]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Carol|url=http://www.hanwayfilms.com/film/carol|publisher=HanWay Films|accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Brooklyn (film)|Brooklyn]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Brooklyn|url=http://www.hanwayfilms.com/film/brooklyn|publisher=HanWay Films|accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref> and ''[[Anomalisa]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Anomalisa|url=http://www.hanwayfilms.com/film/anomalisa|publisher=HanWay Films|accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref> managing director Thorsten Schumacher announced 2015 as \"the most successful year for [HanWay Films] to date.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wiseman|first1=Andreas|title=HanWay Films: a year to remember|url=http://www.screendaily.com/features/hanway-films-a-year-to-remember/5100304.article|website=[[Screen International]]|date=February 13, 2016|accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Team==\n===Executive Board===\n*[[Jeremy Thomas]] - Chairman\n*Peter Watson - Vice Chairman\n*Jan Spielhoff - Chief Operating Officer\n*Joseph Hewitt - Executive Assistant\n\n===Marketing and Publicity===\n*Tom Grievson - Head of Marketing and Distribution\n*Simone Talfourd - Senior Marketing and Distribution Manager\n*Agnes Bobvos - Creative Marketing Assistant\n*Tejinder Jouhal - Senior Marketing & Distribution Manager\n\n===Sales===\n*Marie-Gabrielle Stewart - Managing Director \n*Nicole Mackey - Head of Sales\n*Janina Vilsmaier - Sales Manager\n*Mark Lane - Director of Sales and Distribution, HanWay Select\n*Kate Hide - Business & Content Manager, HanWay Select\n\n===Acquisitions===\n*Matthew Baker - Director of Acquisitions\n*Daniela Ceresa - Acquisitions Executive\n\n===Business Affairs & Finance===\n*Justin Kelly - Head of Business & Legal Affairs\n*Thomas Mann - Business Affairs Executive\n*Elizabeth Kormanova - Director of Business Affairs\n*Mark Thomas - Financial Controller\n\n==Films==\n===1999===\n* ''[[Just Looking]]'' \n* ''[[Tom Donaghy|Story of a Bad Boy]]'' \n* ''[[Women Talking Dirty]]'' \n* ''[[Sunburn (1999 film)|Sunburn]]''\n* ''[[The Cup (1999 film)|The Cup]]'' \n* ''[[Buena Vista Social Club (film)|Buena Vista Social Club]]''\n\n===2000===\n* ''[[Help! I'm a Fish]]''\n* ''[[Brother (2000 film)|Brother]]'' \n* ''[[Innocence (2000 film)|Innocence]]''\n\n===2001===\n* ''[[Lotte Reiniger]]'' \n* ''[[The Mystic Masseur]]'' \n* ''[[The Diaries of Vaslav Nijinsky]]'' \n* ''[[The Triumph of Love (2001 film)|The Triumph of Love]]'' \n* ''[[Love the Hard Way]]'' \n* ''[[The Last Minute]]''\n\n===2002===\n* ''Junimond'' \n* ''Half the Rent'' \n* ''[[Serving Sara]]'' \n* ''[[Revengers Tragedy]]'' \n* ''[[Lost in La Mancha]]'' \n* ''[[Rabbit-Proof Fence]]''\n\n===2003===\n* ''[[House of Sand and Fog (film)|House of Sand and Fog]]'' \n* ''[[The Boys from County Clare]]'' \n* ''[[Festival Express]]'' \n* ''[[Travellers and Magicians]]''\n* ''[[The Dreamers (film)|The Dreamers]]'' \n* ''[[Danny Deckchair]]'' \n* ''[[The Soul of a Man]]'' \n* ''[[Young Adam (film)|Young Adam]]'' \n* ''[[To Kill a King]]'' \n* ''Fools'' \n* ''[[All the Real Girls]]''\n\n===2004===\n* ''[[Night of Truth]]''\n* ''[[It's All Gone Pete Tong]]'' \n* ''[[Human Touch (film)|Human Touch]]''\n* ''[[Land of Plenty]]'' \n* ''[[Promised Land (2004 film)|Promised Land]]''\n* ''Egoshooter'' \n* ''[[Creep (2004 film)|Creep]]''\n* ''[[The Football Factory (film)|The Football Factory]]'' \n* ''[[Derek Jarman#Film and television works prompted by Jarman's life and work|Derek Jarman: Life as Art]]''\n*