ry:Educational institutions established in 1853]]\n[[Category:1853 establishments in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Higher education in Canada]]\n[[Category:Maple League]]\n", "name_user": "Johnsoniensis", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistories:>People", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._Francis_Xavier_University"}
{"title_page": "Denham Springs High School", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=February 2010}}\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Denham Springs High School\n | logo                    = [[File:Denham Springs High School DS Logo.png]]\n | logo_size               = 220px\n | image                   = DenhamSpringsHighSchool.JPG\n | established             = 1897\n | type                    = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n | ceeb                    = 190655\n | us_nces_school_id       = 220102000758\n | principal               = Wesley Howard\n | teaching_staff          = 69.61 {{FTE}}<ref name=NCES/>\n | enrollment              = 1,576 (2017-18)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/globallocator/sch_info_popup.asp?Type=Public&ID=220102000758|title=Denham Springs High School NCES Data|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics}}</ref>\n | ratio                   = 22.64<ref name=NCES/>\n | grades                  = 10\u201312\n | address                 = 1000 [[Louisiana Highway 16|N Range Ave]]\n | city                    = [[Denham Springs, Louisiana|Denham Springs]]\n | state                   = [[Louisiana]]\n | zipcode                 = 70706\n | pushpin_map             = Louisiana#USA\n | country                 = United States\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|30|29|47|N|90|57|22|W|display=inline,title|format=dms|region:US-LA_type:edu_source:gnis}}\n | district                = [[Livingston Parish Public Schools]]\n | us_nces_district_id     = 2201020\n | colors                  = Purple, Yellow, and White\n{{color box|#500078}}&nbsp;{{color box|#FFC715}}&nbsp;{{color box|#FFFFFF}}\n | mascot                  = Butch the Yellow Jacket\n | website                 = {{URL|http://www.denhamspringshs.org/}}\n}}\n\n'''Denham Springs High School''' is a [[State school|public high school]] located in [[Denham Springs, Louisiana|Denham Springs]], [[Louisiana]], USA. Denham Springs High School is a part of the [[Livingston Parish Public Schools|Livingston Parish School System]] and was founded in 1897 as a school for the residents of Denham Springs, a city located in [[Livingston Parish, Louisiana|Livingston Parish]]. The school is located on [[Louisiana Highway 16]], adjacent to [[Denham Springs Freshman High School|Denham Springs Freshman High]]. The school's location makes it prone to flooding. This was the case when [[2016 Louisiana floods|flooding devastated the area in 2016]], and resulted in students having to travel to nearby [[Live Oak High School (Louisiana)|Live Oak High School]] for classes.\n\nDenham Springs High School is a public high school and has open enrollment. The school also consistently ranks high on reports by the Louisiana Department of Education. In the 2019 U.S. News & World Report rankings, Denham Springs High School ranked 43 on the \"Louisiana's Best High Schools\" list.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/louisiana/districts/livingston-parish/denham-springs-high-school-8667|title=Denham Springs High School|website=U.S. & World News Report}}</ref>\n\nDenham Springs High School is a member of the [[Louisiana High School Athletic Association]] and offers a wide variety of sports and programs. Extracurricular activities are also offered in the form of performing arts, school publications, and clubs.\n\n==History==\n\nDenham Springs High School was founded in 1897 for the residents of Denham Springs. The school was built to serve the larger city of Denham Springs so that students would not have to travel as far to attend the Live Oak school that was built two years earlier in 1895. \n\nLivingston Parish Public Schools [[Desegregation in the United States|desegregated]] following the 1969 case Dunn v. Livingston Parish Board.<ref>United States Court of Appeals, Fifth Circuit. ''Dunn v. Livingston Parish School Board''. 14 Aug. 1970. ''Open Jurist''.</ref> The effects of desegregation were largely felt by those at the once all-white Denham Springs High School. The West Livingston School, the only school in the Parish to serve African Americans, saw a large percentage of its students attend Denham Springs High School after desegregation. African American students were harassed by their white students while teachers looked on indifferently.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/news/education/article_f257e7bc-431b-11e8-bb09-7b9463271a7b.html|title=Denham Springs soldier and litigant in Livingston Parish school desegregation case dies|last=Lussier|first=Charles|website=The Advocate|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref> To make matters worse, West Livingston High School was the heart of the African American community in Denham Springs at the time, and after integration, the school system let the school fall into disrepair.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/news/communities/livingston_tangipahoa/article_0a354f6e-198c-11e8-840a-ab7726f450b5.html|title=Educators share experiences of segregation, integration of Livingston schools|last=Couvillion|first=Vic|website=The Advocate|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>\n\nAs the City of Denham Springs continued to grow in the later half of the 20th century, officials at Denham Springs High School looked for ways to continue housing students. On May 8th, 1997, a student caused a fire that destroyed the administrative building and damaged others <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.livingstonparishnews.com/the-making-of-an-activist/article_9fb34a2a-a792-508c-9c44-1fa616d4baa7.html|</ref>, leading to many classrooms continuing in temporary buildings. By 1998, most of the damage was repaired and a new office building was constructed facing the front of the school in 1999. One of the first measures to ease student flow and improve student success was  the addition of [[Denham Springs Freshman High School]] in 1998 as a separate school; having previously been managed as one school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dsfreshmanhigh.org/about-us|title=ABOUT US|website=DSFH|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref> The school has since grown to become the second largest high school in the state of Louisiana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bloximages.newyork1.vip.townnews.com/theadvocate.com/content/tncms/assets/v3/editorial/a/bf/abf15224-e2e2-11e8-a270-7bc64d96ecb6/5be371934b75d.pdf.pdf|title=LHSAA Enrollment Data}}</ref>\n\n[[2016 Louisiana floods|The Great Flood of 2016]] devastated the Denham Springs community. Denham Springs High School was one of the three schools that received substantial damage from the flood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/news/education/article_41d5e010-63c5-11e6-96e2-a389d8742e7a.html|title=Livingston schools hit worst in flooding, but is not alone|last=Lussier|first=Charles|website=The Advocate|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref> As a result of the damages, Denham Springs High School was not able to return to class at their normal campus when classes resumed a month after the flooding event, so students had to travel to Live Oak High School where they attended classes in the afternoon, 40 minutes after the students of Live Oak had their classes.<ref>Vinsanau, Michael. [https://www.wbrz.com/news/livingston-parish-schools-begin-sharing-facilities-on-first-day-back-since-flood/ \"Livingston Parish schools begin sharing facilities on first day back since flood\"]. ''WBRZ.'' Retrieved 2019-06-12.</ref> Although the school received substantial damage, it was not declared a total loss by the [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://garretgraves.house.gov/media-center/in-the-news/flood-repairs-now-complete-all-3-most-damaged-livingston-parish-schools|title=Flood repairs now complete at all but 3 most damaged Livingston Parish schools|date=2018-07-31|website=Congressman Garret Graves|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/flooding-louisiana-students-face-uncertain-school-year/story?id=41589657|title=Fate of Some Louisiana Schools Uncertain After Flooding|last=Shapiro|first=Emily|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref> As a result, the school system was only able to repair the damages while also making minor improvements. There was no work done to prevent future damages from flooding, so the school continued to see issues in 2017 after a heavy rain event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/news/communities/livingston_tangipahoa/article_724e1cfe-7e17-11e7-8317-7b012aada07c.html|title=Water backs up into parts of Denham Springs High during heavy rains; no damage reported|last=report|first=Advocate staff|website=The Advocate|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>\n\n== Enrollment ==\nDenham Springs High School is a public high school with no admissions requirements. Enrollment is open to residents that make up the Denham Springs and Juban communities. Denham Springs High School had 1529 students for the 2015-2016 school year making it the largest in Livingston Parish. The demographics were 1263 (83%) [[Caucasian race|Caucasian]], 160 (10%) [[African Americans|African American]], 81 (5%) [[Hispanic]], 17 (1%) [[Asian Americans|Asian]], 5 (0.3%) [[Native Americans in the United States|American Indian/Alaska Native]], 3(0.1%) [[Multiracial Americans|Two or More Races]]. The school also has a 51:49 male to female ratio.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Academics ==\nDenham Springs High School features a technical-education curriculum and a college-preparatory curriculum with the option to partake in [[Advanced Placement Program|Advanced Placement (AP) Program]]. Students in the technical-education curriculum are required to complete a minimum of 23 academic units that include 4 in English, 4 in mathematics, 2 in science, 2 in social science, 1.5 in physical education, .5 in health, and 9 in their technical pathway. Students in the college-preparatory curriculum are required to complete a minimum of 24 academic units that include 4 in English, 2 in foreign language, 4 in mathematics, 4 in science, 4 in social science, 3 in electives, 1.5 in physical education, .5 in health, and 1 in the arts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/4062d6_df4561047c514f93bcb00f2405fd98db.pdf|title=Denham Springs High School Course Offerings}}</ref>\n\nThe technical-education pathway requires students to travel to the Livingston Parish Literacy and Technical Center in [[Walker, Louisiana|Walker]], Louisiana, and is shared by all of the high schools in Livingston Parish. As of 2019, Denham Springs High School offers 20 AP courses for students to earn college credit. Included in the 20 AP courses is AP Seminar the first course in the [[AP Capstone|AP Capstone Program]].<ref>[https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/courses/ap-capstone/current-ap-capstone-schools?course=ap-capstone-diploma-program \"AP Capstone: Current AP Capstone Schools | AP Central - The College Board\"]</ref> Spanish and Latin are offered to fulfill the foreign language requirement. Students may also enroll concurrently at [[Southeastern Louisiana University]].\n\nFor the 2017-2018 school year, Denham Springs High School earned an A grade under the [[Louisiana Department of Education]] more rigorous grading system with a School Performance Score (SPS) of 94.5. The school has a mean [[ACT (test)|ACT]] score of 21.5. Furthermore, the school has a 87% graduation rate and 59% of its graduates go on to enroll in college.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://louisianaschools.com/schools/32005/academic-performance#student_performance|title=Denham Springs High School {{!}} Louisiana Department of Education|website=louisianaschools.com|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular Activities==\n\n=== Athletics ===\nDenham Springs High School is home to the Lady Jackets' bowling team. They were crowned state champions for four consecutive years. The softball team has also won four state championships, finishing as the Louisiana 5A State runner Up in 2014.\nFootball, however, is the fan and student favorite, drawing crowds of over 5,000 on fall Friday nights in Yellow Jacket Stadium.\n\n=== Performing Arts ===\nDenham Springs High School features one of the most prestigious band programs in the state. The various performing groups include the Jacket Pride Marching Band, a Concert Band, Symphonic Band, and the Denham Springs High School Wind Ensemble that performed at Carnegie Hall<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carnegiehall.org/en/Calendar/2018/02/12/BALDWIN%20WALLACE%20CONSERVATORY%20WIND%20ENSEMBLE%20INVITATIONAL%200930AM|title=Baldwin Wallace Conservatory Wind Ensemble Invitational|website=www.carnegiehall.org|language=en|access-date=2019-10-26}}</ref> in February of 2018. The program is under the direction of Ms. Carlye Latas and Mrs. Jessica Baronet.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Jefferson D. Hughes, III]], member of the [[Louisiana Supreme Court]] since 2013\n* [[Russ Johnson]], Former [[MLB]] player ([[Houston Astros]], [[Tampa Bay Rays]], [[New York Yankees]])\n* [[Ben McDonald]], Former [[MLB]] player ([[Baltimore Orioles]], [[Milwaukee Brewers]])\n* [[Tasmin Mitchell]], Basketball coach and former professional player\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://denhamhs.lpsb.org/default.htm}}\n{{Livingston Parish, Louisiana Schools}}\n\n[[Category:Public high schools in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Schools in Livingston Parish, Louisiana]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=February 2010}}\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Denham Springs High School\n | logo                    = [[File:Denham Springs High School DS Logo.png]]\n | logo_size               = 220\n | image                   = DenhamSpringsHighSchool.JPG\n | established             = 1897\n | type                    = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n | ceeb                    = 190655\n | us_nces_school_id       = 220102000758\n | principal               = Wesley Howard\n | teaching_staff          = 69.61 {{FTE}}<ref name=NCES/>\n | enrollment              = 1,576 (2017-18)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/globallocator/sch_info_popup.asp?Type=Public&ID=220102000758|title=Denham Springs High School NCES Data|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics}}</ref>\n | ratio                   = 22.64<ref name=NCES/>\n | grades                  = 10\u201312\n | address                 = 1000 [[Louisiana Highway 16|N Range Ave]]\n | city                    = [[Denham Springs, Louisiana|Denham Springs]]\n | state                   = [[Louisiana]]\n | zipcode                 = 70706\n | pushpin_map             = Louisiana#USA\n | country                 = United States\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|30|29|47|N|90|57|22|W|display=inline,title|format=dms|region:US-LA_type:edu_source:gnis}}\n | district                = [[Livingston Parish Public Schools]]\n | us_nces_district_id     = 2201020\n | colors                  = Purple, Yellow, and White\n{{color box|#500078}}&nbsp;{{color box|#FFC715}}&nbsp;{{color box|#FFFFFF}}\n | mascot                  = Butch the Yellow Jacket\n | website                 = {{URL|http://www.denhamspringshs.org/}}\n}}\n\n'''Denham Springs High School''' is a [[State school|public high school]] located in [[Denham Springs, Louisiana|Denham Springs]], [[Louisiana]], USA. Denham Springs High School is a part of the [[Livingston Parish Public Schools|Livingston Parish School System]] and was founded in 1897 as a school for the residents of Denham Springs, a city located in [[Livingston Parish, Louisiana|Livingston Parish]]. The school is located on [[Louisiana Highway 16]], adjacent to [[Denham Springs Freshman High School|Denham Springs Freshman High]]. The school's location makes it prone to flooding. This was the case when [[2016 Louisiana floods|flooding devastated the area in 2016]], and resulted in students having to travel to nearby [[Live Oak High School (Louisiana)|Live Oak High School]] for classes.\n\nDenham Springs High School is a public high school and has open enrollment. The school also consistently ranks high on reports by the Louisiana Department of Education. In the 2019 U.S. News & World Report rankings, Denham Springs High School ranked 43 on the \"Louisiana's Best High Schools\" list.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/louisiana/districts/livingston-parish/denham-springs-high-school-8667|title=Denham Springs High School|website=U.S. & World News Report}}</ref>\n\nDenham Springs High School is a member of the [[Louisiana High School Athletic Association]] and offers a wide variety of sports and programs. Extracurricular activities are also offered in the form of performing arts, school publications, and clubs.\n\n==History==\n\nDenham Springs High School was founded in 1897 for the residents of Denham Springs. The school was built to serve the larger city of Denham Springs so that students would not have to travel as far to attend the Live Oak school that was built two years earlier in 1895. \n\nLivingston Parish Public Schools [[Desegregation in the United States|desegregated]] following the 1969 case Dunn v. Livingston Parish Board.<ref>United States Court of Appeals, Fifth Circuit. ''Dunn v. Livingston Parish School Board''. 14 Aug. 1970. ''Open Jurist''.</ref> The effects of desegregation were largely felt by those at the once all-white Denham Springs High School. The West Livingston School, the only school in the Parish to serve African Americans, saw a large percentage of its students attend Denham Springs High School after desegregation. African American students were harassed by their white students while teachers looked on indifferently.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/news/education/article_f257e7bc-431b-11e8-bb09-7b9463271a7b.html|title=Denham Springs soldier and litigant in Livingston Parish school desegregation case dies|last=Lussier|first=Charles|website=The Advocate|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref> To make matters worse, West Livingston High School was the heart of the African American community in Denham Springs at the time, and after integration, the school system let the school fall into disrepair.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/news/communities/livingston_tangipahoa/article_0a354f6e-198c-11e8-840a-ab7726f450b5.html|title=Educators share experiences of segregation, integration of Livingston schools|last=Couvillion|first=Vic|website=The Advocate|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>\n\nAs the City of Denham Springs continued to grow in the later half of the 20th century, officials at Denham Springs High School looked for ways to continue housing students. On May 8th, 1997, a student caused a fire that destroyed the administrative building and damaged others <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.livingstonparishnews.com/the-making-of-an-activist/article_9fb34a2a-a792-508c-9c44-1fa616d4baa7.html|</ref>, leading to many classrooms continuing in temporary buildings. By 1998, most of the damage was repaired and a new office building was constructed facing the front of the school in 1999. One of the first measures to ease student flow and improve student success was  the addition of [[Denham Springs Freshman High School]] in 1998 as a separate school; having previously been managed as one school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dsfreshmanhigh.org/about-us|title=ABOUT US|website=DSFH|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref> The school has since grown to become the second largest high school in the state of Louisiana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bloximages.newyork1.vip.townnews.com/theadvocate.com/content/tncms/assets/v3/editorial/a/bf/abf15224-e2e2-11e8-a270-7bc64d96ecb6/5be371934b75d.pdf.pdf|title=LHSAA Enrollment Data}}</ref>\n\n[[2016 Louisiana floods|The Great Flood of 2016]] devastated the Denham Springs community. Denham Springs High School was one of the three schools that received substantial damage from the flood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/news/education/article_41d5e010-63c5-11e6-96e2-a389d8742e7a.html|title=Livingston schools hit worst in flooding, but is not alone|last=Lussier|first=Charles|website=The Advocate|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref> As a result of the damages, Denham Springs High School was not able to return to class at their normal campus when classes resumed a month after the flooding event, so students had to travel to Live Oak High School where they attended classes in the afternoon, 40 minutes after the students of Live Oak had their classes.<ref>Vinsanau, Michael. [https://www.wbrz.com/news/livingston-parish-schools-begin-sharing-facilities-on-first-day-back-since-flood/ \"Livingston Parish schools begin sharing facilities on first day back since flood\"]. ''WBRZ.'' Retrieved 2019-06-12.</ref> Although the school received substantial damage, it was not declared a total loss by the [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://garretgraves.house.gov/media-center/in-the-news/flood-repairs-now-complete-all-3-most-damaged-livingston-parish-schools|title=Flood repairs now complete at all but 3 most damaged Livingston Parish schools|date=2018-07-31|website=Congressman Garret Graves|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/flooding-louisiana-students-face-uncertain-school-year/story?id=41589657|title=Fate of Some Louisiana Schools Uncertain After Flooding|last=Shapiro|first=Emily|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref> As a result, the school system was only able to repair the damages while also making minor improvements. There was no work done to prevent future damages from flooding, so the school continued to see issues in 2017 after a heavy rain event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/news/communities/livingston_tangipahoa/article_724e1cfe-7e17-11e7-8317-7b012aada07c.html|title=Water backs up into parts of Denham Springs High during heavy rains; no damage reported|last=report|first=Advocate staff|website=The Advocate|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>\n\n== Enrollment ==\nDenham Springs High School is a public high school with no admissions requirements. Enrollment is open to residents that make up the Denham Springs and Juban communities. Denham Springs High School had 1529 students for the 2015-2016 school year making it the largest in Livingston Parish. The demographics were 1263 (83%) [[Caucasian race|Caucasian]], 160 (10%) [[African Americans|African American]], 81 (5%) [[Hispanic]], 17 (1%) [[Asian Americans|Asian]], 5 (0.3%) [[Native Americans in the United States|American Indian/Alaska Native]], 3(0.1%) [[Multiracial Americans|Two or More Races]]. The school also has a 51:49 male to female ratio.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Academics ==\nDenham Springs High School features a technical-education curriculum and a college-preparatory curriculum with the option to partake in [[Advanced Placement Program|Advanced Placement (AP) Program]]. Students in the technical-education curriculum are required to complete a minimum of 23 academic units that include 4 in English, 4 in mathematics, 2 in science, 2 in social science, 1.5 in physical education, .5 in health, and 9 in their technical pathway. Students in the college-preparatory curriculum are required to complete a minimum of 24 academic units that include 4 in English, 2 in foreign language, 4 in mathematics, 4 in science, 4 in social science, 3 in electives, 1.5 in physical education, .5 in health, and 1 in the arts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/4062d6_df4561047c514f93bcb00f2405fd98db.pdf|title=Denham Springs High School Course Offerings}}</ref>\n\nThe technical-education pathway requires students to travel to the Livingston Parish Literacy and Technical Center in [[Walker, Louisiana|Walker]], Louisiana, and is shared by all of the high schools in Livingston Parish. As of 2019, Denham Springs High School offers 20 AP courses for students to earn college credit. Included in the 20 AP courses is AP Seminar the first course in the [[AP Capstone|AP Capstone Program]].<ref>[https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/courses/ap-capstone/current-ap-capstone-schools?course=ap-capstone-diploma-program \"AP Capstone: Current AP Capstone Schools | AP Central - The College Board\"]</ref> Spanish and Latin are offered to fulfill the foreign language requirement. Students may also enroll concurrently at [[Southeastern Louisiana University]].\n\nFor the 2017-2018 school year, Denham Springs High School earned an A grade under the [[Louisiana Department of Education]] more rigorous grading system with a School Performance Score (SPS) of 94.5. The school has a mean [[ACT (test)|ACT]] score of 21.5. Furthermore, the school has a 87% graduation rate and 59% of its graduates go on to enroll in college.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://louisianaschools.com/schools/32005/academic-performance#student_performance|title=Denham Springs High School {{!}} Louisiana Department of Education|website=louisianaschools.com|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular Activities==\n\n=== Athletics ===\nDenham Springs High School is home to the Lady Jackets' bowling team. They were crowned state champions for four consecutive years. The softball team has also won four state championships, finishing as the Louisiana 5A State runner Up in 2014.\nFootball, however, is the fan and student favorite, drawing crowds of over 5,000 on fall Friday nights in Yellow Jacket Stadium.\n\n=== Performing Arts ===\nDenham Springs High School features one of the most prestigious band programs in the state. The various performing groups include the Jacket Pride Marching Band, a Concert Band, Symphonic Band, and the Denham Springs High School Wind Ensemble that performed at Carnegie Hall<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carnegiehall.org/en/Calendar/2018/02/12/BALDWIN%20WALLACE%20CONSERVATORY%20WIND%20ENSEMBLE%20INVITATIONAL%200930AM|title=Baldwin Wallace Conservatory Wind Ensemble Invitational|website=www.carnegiehall.org|language=en|access-date=2019-10-26}}</ref> in February of 2018. The program is under the direction of Ms. Carlye Latas and Mrs. Jessica Baronet.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Jefferson D. Hughes, III]], member of the [[Louisiana Supreme Court]] since 2013\n* [[Russ Johnson]], Former [[MLB]] player ([[Houston Astros]], [[Tampa Bay Rays]], [[New York Yankees]])\n* [[Ben McDonald]], Former [[MLB]] player ([[Baltimore Orioles]], [[Milwaukee Brewers]])\n* [[Tasmin Mitchell]], Basketball coach and former professional player\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://denhamhs.lpsb.org/default.htm}}\n{{Livingston Parish, Louisiana Schools}}\n\n[[Category:Public high schools in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Schools in Livingston Parish, Louisiana]]\n", "name_user": "Smartie988", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor fix to width.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denham_Springs_High_School"}
